   url = { http://dspace.icsy.de/handle/123456789/41 },
   abstract = { Firewalls and Network Address Translators (NATs) are integral components of today&#8217;s Internet infrastructure. Firewalls serve for securing networks against attacks and intrusions and NATs extend the limited address space that is available. Classical client/server applications such as Internet browsing and emails usually work fine with firewalls and NATs. However, firewalls/NATs are often an obstacle for peer-to-peer applications, e.g., Internet telephony, video conferencing and peer-topeer gaming. The problem arises from the fact that peer-to-peer communications often use dynamic port numbers. Since a firewall/NAT can not be pre-configured for every single data flow, the data flows will be blocked or lost. Goal of this thesis is exploring and evaluating currently existing solutions for the described problem. Solutions vary from integrating application intelligence into the firewall/NAT, dynamic configuration of the firewall/NAT by a trusted third party or signaling from the end users to request the traversal of the data flows. The evaluation is based on correctness in different environments (e.g., multi-homed networks, mobile networks), time delay at communication set up, scalability in large networks, efficiency in protocol design, vulnerability to various attacks and costs of deployment and integration into the current networks infrastructure. Based on the evaluation results, this thesis provides a detailed comparison between the different solutions as well as several suggestions to improve them. },
}

