   abstract = { When designing a Grid workflow, it might be necessary to integrate different kinds of services.
In an ideal scenario all services are Grid-enabled. But real workflows often consist of Grid-enabled and
non Grid-enabled services.

One reason is that Grid-enabling services can be costly. Therefore it is favorable to solely Grid-enable the compute-intensive and time-consuming
applications. Additionally, workflows should be allowed to include Grid jobs that execute legacy applications.

Another reason is that very often, third parties charge fees for accessing their services. Hence, it is impossible to convert such 
a third party service into a service that can be integrated into a Grid environment at all.

